<font color="#FF0000">THE TRUE ROAD HAS MANY LANES</font><br>
<tt>Sat Sep 27 17:12:43 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
You have hit upon why I keep pushing the envelop of why we are now what we are.  Those experiences of our training in life and the military or other, prepare us.  Those are gleaned from the experiences of others that would prevent us from learning lessons the hard way.  The evolution of the corp. is built on those experiences.  Korea taught the corp. some very hard lessons.  Training, conditioning, and team work.  A lot of marines lost their lives both in battle and in the POW camps because the pack didn't stay together.  Fight to live, never give up.  Never give your life, make some asshole earn it if he can.  <br><br>
The POW Turks in Korea faired better than anyone.  The pack stayed together, solid.  Doc that's the reason for a pack.  Strength.  Talked to a guy who had given up and wanted to die.  Knew he could shut down, easy.  One of the guys out of desperation went over and pissed on him.  Seems that event gave him focus, intense emotion, purpose.  He survived.<br><br>
Training focus.  A young Marine sniper, first name Danny.  Out on a mission to nail a VC sniper.  Sniper against sniper, things movies are made of.  He found his target.  During the final sighting in he realized he was also a target.  He was looking down the scope of his target.  He held and squeezed just in time to see the other rifle discharge.  Head shot to head shot.  Danny was better, his shot found the mark.  The other shattered his scope, clipped the bridge of his nose and vacuumed out his right eye.  He has a cool patch now.  As far as I know no problems.  Training!<br><br>
The text books leave this out.  In this that stays with the survivors are the answers.  The training never ceases.  We do it now.<br><br>
We are on the correct path and there is more to come.<br>

